Russia and Turkey: a coalition of outsiders?
A gesture that ended in crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and declare an eight-month war of words and economic sanctions officially over.
But when Vladimir Putin greeted his Turkish counterpart in the gilded hall of the St. Petersburg Palace, I got the clear impression that Ankara wants more of this reconciliation.
Yes, we shook hands at the event.
But Putin&#39;s smile looked forced, and he didn&#39;t exactly exude warmth, even by his own subdued standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, kept talking about his &quot;dear friend&quot; Putin - five times, according to one report.
I messed up the bills.
He also vowed that relations with Russia would not only return to the pre-crisis level, but even better.
The next day, newspapers here described Erdogan as behaving as if nothing bad had ever happened.
In my opinion, his enthusiasm was quite the opposite.
But the coolness radiating from Putin showed that the Russian leader has not forgotten anything.
In fact, the cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his opening remarks: when Turkey shot down a Russian warplane on the Syrian border.
Moscow&#39;s reaction at the time was furious.
Putin attacked, accusing Ankara of stabbing Moscow in the back.
The insult was even worse when it came from a supposed friend.
Rebuilding real trust will be difficult, perhaps impossible.
The opinion of the general Russian public has also changed since November.
For months, the state-controlled media led a stunning, all-out attack on Ankara.
Suddenly it seemed that the Turks were to blame for everything.
The most serious were accusations by senior officials that Erdogan&#39;s own family has benefited from the illegal oil trade from ISIS-controlled areas of Syria.
He has emphatically denied this.
But the official message in St. Petersburg was that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting only happened because Putin got the apology he demanded from President Erdogan.
Russia achieved some sort of victory.
The benefits of agreeing to a ceasefire for Ankara are clear.
First, Erdogan needs all the friends he can get after he was nearly ousted from power in a failed coup last month.
The ongoing terrorist attacks in Turkey have also clearly shaken him.
In addition, there is a financial motive.
Russia&#39;s economic sanctions have been heavy, especially the ban on chartered flights, which usually carry several million Russian tourists to the Turkish coast each year.
The number has decreased by almost 90 percent.
As for Russia, local tour operators and charter airlines will certainly be relieved when flights finally resume.
They are hoping for a late season rush to the Mediterranean.
And already this week, state TV has predicted cheaper fruit and vegetables after the import of agricultural products from Turkey is allowed again.
&quot;Tourists there, tomatoes back here,&quot; as the Vedemosti newspaper&#39;s report put it.
But the visit also had added political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry with the West for what is seen as a weak response to the attempted coup.
Add to that a long-standing grudge against EU membership negotiations that progressed at a snail&#39;s pace, and Putin emerges, eager to take advantage of the coolness and erode Turkey&#39;s ties to the West.
The Russian leader was guaranteed to get points from Ankara, where he called after the attempted revolution to support the appointed authorities.
Of course, this is a solution for Moscow, which has its own deep-rooted fear of a change of power.
So this meeting in a lavish seaside palace allowed Russia and Turkey to introduce the “alignment of outsiders,” as one analyst described the situation to me: two countries that feel they have been abandoned and mistreated by the West, joining forces.
However, despite the public reconciliation, the two have major differences.
The key issue is Syria, where Moscow has recently adapted itself to the role of peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey support opposing sides.
It may be telling that after nearly three hours of preliminary discussions, the presidents told the press that they had not even discussed the issue.
The Turkish president deliberately avoided answering a question about their differences, while Putin chose to highlight them.
There is no clear consensus on where they can look for common ground on Syria.
After months of open hostility, and given the possibility of a full-blown disaster if NATO member Turkey shoots down a Russian fighter jet, it is surely better that the two leaders are even on speaking terms again.
