Pokémon Go is a respectable hunt for health and happiness
It&#39;s fascinating to see how the world is changing.
Over the past decade, many have been concerned that teenagers and children are no longer going out to play, but prefer to spend their free time watching screens.
Pokémon Go gets people off the couch and into an activity.
Screen time was initially limited to television, then to video games, and now more recently to smartphones.
So it&#39;s great to see that technology and outdoor activity are not mutually exclusive.
I am of course referring to the craze called Pokémon Go. For an app based on characters originally developed in the 1990s for video games (later spawned a cartoon series, playing cards, and other spin-offs).
Like many pop culture phenomena, its popularity had somewhat faded before the release of this new game in the US, Australia and New Zealand in early July.
After that, the release of the game in other countries was delayed, as the huge popularity overloaded the servers.
In just days, Pokémon Go had more users than Tinder and almost as many as Twitter.
So how does it work?
Explained in a nutshell, players use their smartphones to search for Pokémon, which are tracked using GPS, and when found, can be &quot;photographed&quot; (using a screenshot on the phone) or &quot;caught&quot;.
The generation that played the game when they were younger has joined the craze and jumped off the couch to join the quest.
In the US, the game has led to a significant increase in the daily steps taken by the &quot;average person&quot;.
Cardiogram, an Apple Watch app that tracks 35,000 users, recently told the Washington Post that within two days of the game&#39;s release, the number of people exercising 30 minutes a day jumped from 45 percent to 53 percent of users tracked by Cardiogram.
The company doesn&#39;t know who&#39;s playing Pokémon Go, it only sees training level information.
Many public health campaigns calling for &quot;get 30&quot;, &quot;get off the couch&quot; and &quot;be active every day&quot; have failed because most public health warnings are boring and delivered by people who look unhappy.
However, the importance of exercise cannot be underestimated.
People who exercise regularly have a lower risk of getting cancer or depression.
Activity helps with weight control, high blood pressure and diabetes. Its benefits are too numerous to list here.
The beauty of Pokémon Go is that it gets people to go out and do something they enjoy.
This covers the three pillars of health: exercise, fresh air and sunshine, and fun.
Some people even make new friends while hunting.
As usual, disapproving pranksters are looking for things to complain about here.
Yes, someone can walk towards the door.
So what?
There has been a breakthrough.
While there have been apps like Fitbit to track activity in the past, they didn&#39;t give you a reason to move the way this game does.
The allure of novelty disappears and use subsides over time.
However, due to the success of Pokémon, other games are coming that combine apps and virtual reality with real-world activity, helping many people who hunt to be more active, fitter and healthier.
