One step ahead of the robber - criminal intelligence helps in solving crimes and reveals serious crime - ESS.fi
Since the beginning of 2014, each of Finland&#39;s 11 police departments has had an RTA, or crime intelligence and analysis unit.
The operation of the unit is invisible to the outside.
In the Häme Police Department, the unit includes a total of four policemen in Lahti and Hämeenlinna.
It is run by a senior constable stationed in Lahti.
The inspector in Lahti acts as the pavement supervisor.
In addition, the strength of the unit includes a civilian dedicated to information technology in Hämeenlinna.
Everyone works in civilian clothes.
The unit has proven its usefulness and necessity, says deputy police chief Tero Seppänen.
The RTA unit produces various reports for the rest of the police.
In Häme, it has, among other things, acquired information on asylum seekers.
The latest reform of working methods
The establishment of analysis units is the most recent reform of police working methods.
The goal has been to prevent crimes, that is, that the police would go to the scene less and less often, blowing their whistles, only when they receive an alarm.
With the help of the information collected and analyzed by the unit, daily police activities are targeted where it is most needed.
Along with the reform of the police administration, one criminal intelligence center was established in the country, three national units under it, and each police department has its own criminal intelligence unit.
The PTR center, which operates in Vantaa in connection with the Central Criminal Police, manages operations nationwide.
As the name suggests, PTR units are staffed by people from the Police, Customs and the Border Guard.
RTA units, on the other hand, work in areas divided by police departments, and their task is to provide information to both local police forces and national units.
The inquiry extends beyond one&#39;s own area
Whereas an individual police officer knows what has happened during his 12-hour shift, the role of the RTA unit is to know what is happening in the entire police department.
Intelligence also extends beyond the borders of one&#39;s own institution, because so does crime.
Those working in the RTA unit have better computer skills than the basic police.
With the help of registers, alert task database and observations, the unit aims to draw the police&#39;s attention to new phenomena, prolific criminals or similar crimes.
This is called serialization and is one of the most important tools in criminal investigation.
All people have their own way of doing things.
A handprint can also be seen at work, be it honest or criminal.
Based on the way of doing it, a certain kind of image is formed of the author.
Serialization can be done either on the basis of the act or the person, depending on which one the police have more information about.
Criminals learn from their mistakes
The employees of the RTA unit do not walk around the city with their collars up, but their work is not completely public either.
The methods used by the criminals as well as their own are not disclosed, because it could lead to professional criminals developing their activities and thus trying to prevent the police&#39;s crime prevention efforts.
The police informs the public about the methods if it anticipates that they will cause a threat.
Such a case was, for example, the method of marking vacant apartments used in apartment burglaries, which was reported in the early summer.
In it, the perpetrators put a stick, a pin or a piece of tape in the front door of the apartment, which they used to test whether the residents are really away.
The preliminary investigation material is public at least to the parties involved.
The analysis unit has found that the most professional criminals learn from their mistakes.
The wittiest ones order the minutes of the district court, from which it may appear, for example, that fingerprints have been found at the scene.
Next time, let&#39;s go to the thieves with gloves in hand.
Deputy police chief Tero Seppä from the Häme police, inspector Tuomo Lepola from the Eastern Finland police, crime inspector Sami Joutjärve from the Joensuu police station and crime inspector Arto Tuomela from the central crime police have been interviewed for the case.
The police collects and analyzes information, which is used to plan practical activities.
In the background, the reduction in the amount of labor and funding.
The first steps towards a new operating method were already taken 30 years ago.
The most recent change was the three-phase PORA reform, which ended at the end of 2013.
With national cooperation, information is gathered from outside the own institution and the borders of Finland.
