Horrifying archival discovery: hundreds of thousands of women wanted to give birth to children for the Nazis - the register also includes Finns
In his recent Dagens Nyheter article, journalist Christopher Andersson writes how the US National Archives in Maryland has microfilmed documents concerning a total of 218,500 women, all of whom wanted to marry SS men.
Most of the women are German, but there are also American, French, Dutch and Russian women.
In addition, at least 65 Danes, 86 Norwegians, 14 Finns and 31 Swedish women wanted to be Nazi brides.
The documents and registration cards come from the racial office that operated in Nazi Germany.
The Racial Office operated under SS leader Heinrich Himmler.
No SS man in Nazi Germany was allowed to have children until he had been examined by an SS doctor.
The same applied to an even greater extent for women who had to be able to give birth to more than 10 children.
According to Andersson, gynecological examinations were performed on the women to clarify the matter.
The Racial Agency found out the women&#39;s backgrounds, among other things, by examining church records.
The purpose was to ensure that there were no Jews in the women&#39;s family tree.
The women also had to be ready to give up their Swedish citizenship and provide the breed office with handwritten biographies and good recommendations from relatives.
The Race Office wanted guarantees that the women were &quot;child-loving&quot;, &quot;thrifty&quot;, and &quot;good National Socialists&quot; who knew German well.
Women who did not meet the requirements were not accepted as brides for SS men.
The story does not tell what happened to the 14 Finnish women found in the archive&#39;s documents.
SS leaders created a state-sponsored program known as Lebensborn in 1936.
Among other things, the program stipulated that every SS man should have four children, either in or out of wedlock.
Lebensborn homes take care of children born out of wedlock and their mothers.
However, the program was not promoted very actively, according to the website of the American Holocaust Museum.
Instead, Nazi population policy focused on the family and marriage.
The state encouraged marriage by offering loans and supported having children.
The German Mother&#39;s Cross of Honor was awarded to women who had given birth to at least four children.
In Nazi Germany, marriages between &quot;Aryans&quot; and &quot;non-Aryans&quot; were prohibited by law, the museum&#39;s website states.
