In June, the British surprised even themselves by voting their kingdom out of the EU.
In the end, 52 percent of the voters supported leaving and 48 percent would have remained in the union, even though opinion polls during the voting week predicted the opposite result.
British economists and economic institutions were almost unanimously in favor of remaining in the EU.
Not a single prestigious research institute or university voted for the separation, although a couple of individual researchers did not agree with the mainstream of their profession.
The basic mantra of Western politics, former US President Bill Clinton&#39;s recent election campaign theme phrase &quot;It&#39;s the economy, stupid&quot; flew into the scrap heap in the UK&#39;s Brexit vote.
Economists were shocked when their voices were not heard.
They were shocked when the economy didn&#39;t even seem to be the most important thing in politics.
Financial jargon
In its latest monthly survey, the Center for Macroeconomics asks the profession for answers to the Brexit disaster.
The most typical answer is that the economists were not listened to, because this time the voters made the decision on other than economic grounds.
One explanation given by economists for the loss of economic status is that people do not understand economics.
Many people still have the idea that the number of jobs is independent of the number of people working, so almost constant.
If an immigrant gets a job, it will be taken away from a real Briton.
Many also have the idea that a decrease in the value of the currency would be a good thing because it would promote the export industry.
In the opinion of the economists, the voters did not believe the economic arguments, because the consensus of the economists was not sufficiently presented.
They were particularly annoyed by the fairness of the BBC, which gave as much space to economists in favor of leaving the EU, representing only a couple of percent of the economists, as to the overwhelming majority.
The EU-hostile press was not interested in telling what the IFS, IFM, BoE, CEPR and LSE and other combinations of economic powerhouses think about the consequences of the separation.
Those distant letter combinations spoke facelessly about economic growth, trade relations, national debt and currency.
And if the economists&#39; messages were both listened to and understood, they were not taken care of, because the economists represent an elite with whom the voters, in their own opinion, have no common interests.
Academics in big cities like economists would have stayed in the EU, but the message was not effective in small towns and rural areas.
Immigration is also an economy
The overwhelming winning argument for the Brexit vote was about immigration.
An immigrant takes your job, an immigrant overcrowds your hospital, an immigrant takes advantage of you.
These arguments are valid.
Every cafe has foreign workers.
How many more jobs would the Brits have if they left?
You see immigrants in the waiting room of every health center.
How much easier would it be for Britons to get doctor&#39;s appointments if they didn&#39;t exist?
There are children of immigrants in every school.
How much easier would it be for the children of real Britons to get a place at school if they got rid of them?
Foreigners live in every municipality.
How much more space would the natives have if they faded away?
I think these are economic issues.
They concern jobs, housing and public services.
However, economists did not manage to answer them, and even if they did, their answers did not get visibility.
Economists failed to explain that thanks to immigrants, Britons have more jobs, fewer queues at health centers and more money for education and social security.
Immigrants - and EU immigrants in particular - are net contributors to the British public finances, and their consumption creates jobs.
Aberdeen real estate fund braced for Brexit with cash
One of the funds was Aberdeen Asset Management, whose real estate investments are managed by Finnish Pertti Vanhanen.
According to him, Aberdeen was prepared in time for Brexit by preparing plans A and B.
Plan B, i.e. the victory of the EU-leave camp, began to be prepared in more detail a few weeks before the vote, just in case the result was Leave.
The concern was that investors would start pulling their funds out of the market.
Real estate funds do not normally have large liquid assets, but now they might be needed.
We went to increase cash reserves.
When Brexit happened on the 23rd, we had 25 percent of the fund&#39;s investments in cash or liquid assets, Vanhanen says of Aberdeen&#39;s only open daily quoted real estate fund, which was affected by the news.
According to Vanhanen, the normal level would be 15-20 percent.
The value of the fund at the time was £3.5 billion.
In total, the company&#39;s funds are worth around £20 billion.
It was the highest amount in nine open-end real estate funds, Vanhanen says of all open-end real estate funds in the UK.
He estimates that the lowest amount of cash in these funds was ten percent or even less.
Real estate funds therefore prepared for Brexit with very different strategies.
Funds closed trading
When the pro-EU exit camp won, Europe went haywire.
However, the two weeks following the vote in the real estate market were quite calm, Vanhanen says.
Then two things happened that changed the situation.
The first was the speech of Mark Carney, Governor of the Bank of England, in which he estimated that Brexit could be a big risk for commercial real estate operators.
In addition, the first of the real estate funds, Standard Life, froze its trading.
Together, they seized the situation and brought it to the headlines of the Financial Times and the BBC.
The situation was immediately compared to 2007 and 2008, says Vanhanen.
This made investors nervous.
Institutional investors remained calmer, but private investors got nervous.
The snowball started rolling, and fund after fund had to close its doors.
Aberdeen was doing well because of the cash raised, but it too eventually had to freeze trading for six days.
According to Vanhanen, they did not actually close trading, but changed the pricing downwards.
In practice, according to him, investors were given time to consider whether it is worth pulling money out in a panic.
Aberdeen&#39;s message was that if you don&#39;t have to take your money out now, it&#39;s not worth it because it would result in losses.
That calmed the situation down, and most canceled the announcement.
After that, it was quite steady, and now the market has been very calm for a couple of weeks, Vanhanen says.
He points out that, for example, Aberdeen&#39;s continental European funds have not experienced any similar upheaval.
However, there were a lot of inquiries.
Unreasonable attention to real estate funds
In Vanhanen&#39;s opinion, the closures of real estate fund transactions received an unreasonable amount of attention.
The open-ended funds affected by the closures control around four per cent of UK real estate.
Aberdeen&#39;s closure lasted six days and the company sold off less than ten of its 80 properties in London.
Some other funds are still closed.
Aviva Investors warned its investors this week that it may hold onto its fund until mid-2017.
There is uncertainty in the air at the moment, and economic growth forecasts have been slashed downwards, but the situation does not look any &quot;wilder&quot; for Aberdeen.
The biggest questions now concern the future development of the British economy.
Despite the uncertainty, the situation has even brought some real estate investors new opportunities, Vanhanen points out.
The exchange rate between the pound and the dollar is at its weakest in 30 years, and the market is also 15 percent off compared to the time before the Brexit vote.
A dollar buyer can now buy the same property for up to 30 percent less.
There are many willing buyers, Vanhanen says.
Brexit brought disadvantages to the London real estate market
At two in the morning, the situation still didn&#39;t look too bad.
But at four, when Pertti Vanhanen, who is responsible for real estate investments at the British real estate fund Aberdeen Asset Management, woke up again to look at the results of the Brexit vote, the situation was different.
That&#39;s all there was to it.
I realized that this is now going towards plan B, says Vanhanen in his second home in Helsinki.
He immediately headed to work.
The City of London was already fully alive despite the early night.
In the office, the TV screens, normally set to silent, played the news, and the normally loud crowd went completely silent to listen when Prime Minister David Cameron stepped in front of the camera this morning to announce his resignation.
When the market opened, the display terminals flashed nothing but red.
It was the kind of morning you never thought you would live, says Vanhanen.
Not because, despite the turmoil, Aberdeen, one of Britain&#39;s largest real estate funds, completed two real estate transactions the day after the Brexit vote, i.e. Midsummer.
The atmosphere was mixed.
However, the company was well prepared for the alternative, and that&#39;s why the situation was kind of calm, Vanhanen says.
The Brexit vote started a correction movement
The vote was followed by a storm.
The pound collapsed, the British leadership changed.
The market began to anticipate drastic declines in the real estate market in Britain and especially in London.
Losses of up to 20 percent were predicted for London office space in the coming years.
Soon a number of UK real estate funds began to freeze their trading one after another.
Aberdeen also did so for six days.
Now the storm has subsided, but there is still uncertainty in the air.
However, it is not visible on the face of Vanhanen, who spent his last days of summer vacation in Helsinki this week.
In his opinion, it is still too early to say much about what will follow from Brexit.
So much is still open: how the separation will happen and how Scotland will react to the situation, for example.
Initial information on the development of the London real estate market has already been received.
Real estate service company CBRE&#39;s information on price development covers about a third of the market.
According to them, the prices of all properties in London fell by 3.3 percent from June to July.
In the office buildings of the City of London, the minus accumulated 6.1 percent, Vanhanen lists.
The numbers are not that terrible, but they are monthly changes.
The monthly index started to be published in 1987, and there have been worse figures in only five months, says Vanhanen.
All drops of equal magnitude occurred in the crisis years of 2007 and 2008.
It is also interesting because Brexit was compared quite quickly to the collapse of Lehman and the global financial crisis that started from the US real estate market.
In Vanhanen&#39;s opinion, the comparison is not quite apt, because now we are dealing with Britain&#39;s home-grown crisis.
The atmosphere is also different.
The real estate market has not seen panic sales like those times, but a willingness to sell to improve liquidity, says Vanhanen.
Financing is normally available as well.
The repair shop could have been ahead anyway
In fact, the price correction movement is not a miracle for him - such a thing could have been ahead even without Brexit.
According to Aberdeen&#39;s assessment, real estate prices in London and other world-leading cities have been too high for years.
We have been saying for two years that the City and especially the offices are overpriced, says Vanhanen.
So the fall started really high.
Prices in London have risen for four reasons, Vanhanen lists.
The British economy has grown strongly, as has London&#39;s population.
Another big trend is that real estate is the last ownership class to globalize, Vanhanen says.
New players have entered the market from the Middle East and Asia, and more and more institutions and even private investors are looking for real estate investment targets abroad.
As a well-known city, London is an easy destination.
In addition, prices have been fueled by low interest rates, which has forced pension companies, for example, to look for income from new targets.
On top of this, loans have been easily available - although, according to Vanhanen, leverage has been used clearly less now than during the boom before the 2008 crisis.
Scatter, scatter
In London, the rise in prices leveled off last summer, Vanhanen says.
Aberdeen also started to lighten its holdings in London, and was a net seller last year.
Some kind of twist was expected, and now it came.
What next?
It depends on how the British national economy develops, says Vanhanen.
He does not dare to estimate much about the future, but says that there is hardly any upswing.
The mood suggests that there is a downward or steady trend ahead.
Vanhanen has already seen several moves up and down, as he has been in the real estate industry since 1988.
And he is still an optimist who believes that potholes can be overcome with work.
If you are well prepared for risks, you are in a better position.
He believes in global decentralization.
If you have invested in one market, you are too much its victim.
If it has been decentralized, the risks have also been decentralized, says Vanhanen.
