Grönberg is optimistic about the idea.
School in Kirkkonummi
The training of the Heila puppy is coordinated by the Tulli dog school located in Kirkkonummi.
Suntio goes to train with Heila also with experts from the police and the Defense Forces.
The police have strong experience in training dogs and the Defense Forces have expertise in explosives.
Customs together with other authorities decide which smells Heila will be taught to recognize.
Heila is always given further training as needed, says Grönberg.
Heila&#39;s colleagues in Helsinki-Vantaa are Customs&#39; six drug dogs and money and drug dog Massi.
Labrador retriever Heila has been chosen from a litter of ten puppies.
The selection criteria of a dog for the airport include agility and hunting spirit, as well as calmness, because the dog deals with weapons, explosives and crowds of people.
Heila, who lives in Suntio&#39;s home, is a close colleague of the customs inspector, but also a family member.
You can&#39;t do anything without Heila at home, Suntio laughs.
Subtle orders are sent to Heila from a single layer.
Ilta-Sanomi&#39;s cameraman loses the cover of the camera&#39;s microphone to a fast dog, but Heila returns the cover that looks like a soft toy immediately after the &quot;let go&quot; command.
There is a lot of competition for working dogs
Heila&#39;s initial training will be completed next year.
There are still level exams ahead, next in October, where it is assessed whether the training is sufficient for demanding work tasks.
Heila can be seen working in Helsinki-Vantaa next year, if everything goes according to plan.
Unfortunately, passengers cannot come and pet a dog wearing a work vest, reminds Suntio.
The costs of one working dog are around 60,000-70,000 euros per year for customs.
Their working life is about seven to eight years, even ten, after which they retire to the care of their owner.
The working days can be long, from eight to ten hours, but the active work sections only last from ten minutes to a couple of hours.
There is a lot of competition at Customs to become the owner of working dogs.
