Snapchat&#39;s &quot;anime&quot; effect is criticized as an Asian caricature
According to Snapchat, anime inspired the filter, but some observers say it&#39;s racist.
With its lens tool, Snapchat allows its roughly 150 million daily users to reshape reality and play with identity in ways that are almost ridiculous.
You can transform yourself into a pineapple, a dog or a character that would fit in a Roy Lichtenstein painting.
Lenses are simple, face-contorting tools that produce more than 30 million enhanced selfies a day.
All missteps quickly end up in public documents.
Snapchat&#39;s lenses have previously been criticized with accusations that the application promotes a blackface mask or favors bleached skin as the ideal of beauty.
So when Snapchat this week promoted a lens that gave some users crooked eyes, crooked teeth and chubby cheeks, some critics called it a racist caricature of Asian people - &quot;yellowface&quot;.
And they wonder if these recurring controversies could be a sign of a larger problem with diversity at the company.
The news and outrage spread widely on Wednesday with reports from The Verge and Motherboard, a day later Snapchat said it had ended the feature.
The company offered an explanation: The lens was intended as a tribute to anime characters, not a caricature of Asians.
But for observers who experienced racism, the lens was a reminder of offensive stereotypes in action.
Others vehemently denied the anime comparison.
Grace Sparapani, a Korean-American art student whose tweet about the photos was widely shared, said in an email that the lens was &quot;offensive and uncomfortable to say the least.&quot;
He added that &quot;it&#39;s hard to argue against a comparison where a gross Asian caricature and filter effects are side by side.&quot;
It shows that the filter is not just yellowface, but yellowface taken to the extreme of vilification.
Snapchat isn&#39;t the only company crossing these cultural traps.
From corporate boardrooms to Hollywood to the devices we all carry in our hands, American culture seems caught in a never-ending struggle for diversity and inclusion.
And Snapchat&#39;s huge audience of young people, more racially diverse than their parents, may mean they&#39;re even more likely to expect an understanding attitude.
25-year-old Katie Zhu said in an interview on Thursday that when one of Snapchat&#39;s lenses creates an offensive image, &quot;it&#39;s a lot harder for these guys to be inconspicuous than before.&quot;
On Thursday, Zhu, a product manager and engineer working for Medium, decided to delete his Snapchat account and urged others to do the same.
In an op-ed for Medium and in a phone interview, he said he believes the racial controversies reflect a lack of diversity in Snapchat&#39;s hiring practices.
Zhu criticized the company&#39;s predominantly white male management and ended his post with the hashtag #DeleteSnapchat
“Either they don&#39;t have a diversity of color on their staff that allows them to make these kinds of decisions,” said Zhu, who is Chinese-American, “or they have people of color on the job, but they&#39;re not in positions where they feel safe or can speak up. &quot;
Other observers share his sentiment, a complaint that Snapchat has largely gone unanswered.
The company does not publish figures on the diversity of its staff, noting its status as a private company.
On Thursday, Snapchat declined to discuss the racial backgrounds of its staff, but a representative said the company recently hired a recruiter to focus on underrepresented populations and advance internal inclusion efforts.
For her part, Zhu said she will keep her Snapchat account closed, adding: &quot;Is it so that they actually need more users like us to say this is not ok.&quot;
According to a congressional panel, military officials falsified ISIS intelligence
In a report released Thursday, a congressional panel said officials at the U.S. military&#39;s military theater headquarters manipulated intelligence reports to present a more optimistic picture of the war against ISIS in Iraq and Syria than the events on the ground warranted.
An interim report by a task force set up by the Republican chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, the Intelligence Committee and the Defense Appropriations Subcommittee found &quot;widespread dissatisfaction&quot; among headquarters intelligence analysts who said superiors tampered with their assessments of American efforts to defeat ISIS.
The headquarters, known as Centcom, is the headquarters of the Armed Forces War Zone in Tampa, Florida, which oversees the operations of the United States Armed Forces in the Middle East and Central Asia.
“Intelligence outputs accepted by senior Centcom leaders typically painted a more positive picture of US counterterrorism efforts than the facts on the ground warranted. They were consistently more positive than the analyzes produced by other factors in the intelligence community,&quot; the report&#39;s press release said.
&quot;What happened at Centcom is unacceptable - our warfighters suffer when poor analysis is presented to high-ranking decision makers,&quot; said Rep. Ken Calvert, R-Calif.
Centcom&#39;s management failures reach the very top of the organization.
The 10-page report details persistent problems with headquarters&#39; descriptions and analyzes of US efforts to train Iraqi forces in 2014 and 2015.
While it does not provide clear evidence that senior Obama administration officials ordered the reports to be tampered with, it suggests that analysts felt pressured by Centcom leaders to portray the threat posed by the Islamic State, ISIS, in a more positive light.
&quot;Throughout the first half of 2015, many of the headquarters&#39; press releases, statements, and testimony to Congress were significantly more positive than the events themselves,&quot; the report said.
For example, a Centcom official stated publicly that a major offensive to retake Mosul could begin even as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq&#39;s second largest city, is still under ISIS control.
&quot;After months of investigation, this is very clear,&quot; Representative Mike Pompeo, Republican of Kansas, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, the highest-ranking intelligence leaders at the headquarters of the US military&#39;s military domain manipulated the headquarters&#39; intelligence output to downplay the threat of ISIS in Iraq.
Republicans created the task force after hearing that analysts had raised concerns that intelligence on the Islamic State group was being manipulated.
The report published on Thursday will be followed by more extensive results while the investigation is ongoing.
The Inspector General of the Ministry of Defense has begun an additional, ongoing investigation into Centcom&#39;s intelligence.
Democratic members of the House Intelligence Committee released their own findings Thursday, which agreed with some of the Republican task force&#39;s conclusions.
&quot;Between 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an unnecessarily insular process for assessing intelligence on ISIS and Iraqi security forces,&quot; Representative Adam B. Schiff, the committee&#39;s top Democrat, said in a statement.
According to Schiff, this process &quot;delayed the release of intelligence outputs&quot;, worsened sentiment among analysts and &quot;didn&#39;t allow enough room for divergent viewpoints&quot;.
Schiff and Democrats said they found no evidence that the White House tried to pressure Centcom analysts to fit their findings into a &quot;preset or political narrative.&quot;
The Daily Beast reported on Tuesday the preliminary results of the congressional investigation.
Last August, The New York Times reported that the Pentagon&#39;s inspector general had opened an investigation following complaints from Centcom analysts.
Commander Capt. Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Defense Department will not comment on the congressional report while the inspector general&#39;s investigation is ongoing.
But he said that &quot;experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and the intelligence community and the Department of Defense welcome a healthy dialogue about these vital national security topics.&quot;
The research has other ramifications than just whether the US-led bombing campaign in Iraq and Syria is succeeding (as a growing number of defense officials now claim).
Last year&#39;s allegations called into question how much President Obama can trust headquarters to provide honest assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis hotspots.
The criticism of Islamic State intelligence echoes a controversy more than a decade ago, when Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker wrote a research paper saying that, despite the objections of many analysts, President George W. Bush&#39;s administration supported a small force in Iraq and spent very little time considering what sanctions the 2003 the attack would have.
Hooker also played a key role in the rebellion regarding Islamic State intelligence.
Officials said last year Hooker&#39;s team concluded that, despite public statements to the contrary, airstrikes against Islamic State-controlled refineries had not significantly weakened the terrorist group&#39;s economy because it had built makeshift refineries to sell oil through the black market.
However, The Times reported in September that this discovery was not communicated outside of headquarters.
Centcom&#39;s then-commander, Gen. Lloyd J. Austin III, came under fire last year after many lawmakers saw his testimony to the Senate as an overly positive assessment of the war.
General Austin retired in April and was replaced at headquarters by General Joseph L. Votel.
