Trampoline peace in the middle of the Olympic frenzy
Wherever you are, whatever time it is, the Olympics are on.
The events of Rio de Janeiro feel continuous and inevitable, a furious message of competition and effort.
Just as if the Olympic torch itself were a flaming baton passed from archer to swimmer and gymnast to triathlete.
It&#39;s impossible to turn on the TV, read a newspaper, or listen to a neighbor&#39;s conversation in line at a coffee shop without hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky, or the feud between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
And then there&#39;s Logan Dooley.
Dooley, a first-time Olympian and future heartthrob with dimples, could well be one of those prime-time household names, backed by sponsorship deals and feel-good TV commercials - if she were a swimmer, a gymnast or even a fencer.
But Dooley, 28, of Lake Forest, Calif., is competing for Olympic gold on the trampoline.
The Olympic flame does not illuminate all sports equally.
Farther from the center, partly in the shadows, are the sports that are not generally accepted by everyone: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
We always have breaststroke, long live it.
But if I may make a moderate number about my particular favorite, I would like to draw attention to the understated charm of the trampoline.
Although trampoline has been an Olympic sport since 2000, when it made its debut at the Sydney Games, its presence has been so little noticed in the intervening 16 years that many I interviewed had no idea it was an Olympic sport.
This may be regional ignorance.
Although the United States has sent athletes to compete in the sport, it has never won a medal in it and did not have an athlete advance to the finals until 2012.
The Chinese and Russians usually share the men&#39;s medals, while the Chinese and Canadians share the women&#39;s medals.
This year China&#39;s Dong Dong and Canada&#39;s Rosie McLennan are defending their London gold medals.
Trampoline, however, has a certain underdog allure, partly because to the uncivilized ear it sounds more suited to clown school than the Olympics.
Here I must confess that I am no expert, just a fan of the flightless.
The sport has possibilities for fun, as can be seen from the vibration of endless bounces in cartoons, but it also has the stealthiness of gymnastics and diving, two sports that are basically combined in it.
The word &quot;trampoline&quot; comes from the Spanish word el trampolín, which means springboard.
Champs jump up to a height of almost 30 feet on a giant trampoline and must complete a series of twists and turns (flips, flips, and flips) before landing on their feet.
According to the official Olympic program, they are judged on execution, difficulty and &quot;flight time&quot;.
32 athletes from 17 countries will compete in Rio, 16 men and 16 women.
The most common direction of the Olympics is straight ahead.
Those hoping for a medal must go further, faster, up and over in search of gold - sometimes to the finish line, sometimes back and forth around the field.
They are hunting not only the finish line or the starting wall, but also, in the televised coverage, another elusive limit: the world or Olympic record.
This determined pursuit is noble, admirable and even fanatical - and it can even move the viewer to tears.
But that&#39;s also the reason why even watching the games can be a bit exhausting.
The trampoline offers a moment of rest here.
The direction of the trampoline is up.
The goal is not to move forward.
The competitor rises to another ascent, appearing weightless like an astronaut, goes up, then down, then effortlessly up again.
Of course, there is no lack of competition or difficulty in this, but during the program there is no furious rush towards the end, no leaps into the distance, only a dreamy, fluid suspension of time and gravity.
It&#39;s as close to a zen state as you can get at the Olympics.
The women&#39;s heats and then the finals will be held on Friday afternoon starting at 1pm ET, with the men&#39;s heats also on Saturday at 1pm.
NBC will air the finals as part of its afternoon schedule beginning at 2 p.m. both days.
In the middle of the Olympic frenzy, they offer a quiet, charming moment that will probably not be noticed in the general chaos.
And if awareness is only achieved by offering male athletes to be stared at and objectified (as the US male gymnasts recently suggested, according to The Wall Street Journal ), Dooley is just waiting for his new fan base to sigh.
A &quot;generation is showing its mind&quot; in Ethiopia, a longtime US ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Protesters demanding political change in Ethiopia have faced violent opposition from the government.
Witnesses say dozens of protesters have been shot dead in clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia breaking apart?
Over the past decade, it has been one of Africa&#39;s most stable nations, a staunch ally of the West, with a rapidly growing economy.
However, in recent months, anti-government protests have shaken the country as they spread to more and more areas.
Last week alone, thousands of people took to the streets demanding fundamental political change.
According to human rights groups, the government&#39;s response was relentless.
Witnesses said police shot and killed dozens of unarmed protesters.
Widespread videos recorded at the protests, believed to be late last year or early this year, show security officials beating young people with batons while forcing them to stand with their hands against a wall.
The main human rights authority of the United Nations is now demanding a thorough investigation.
&quot;Keeping this country together was always difficult, and it will be even more difficult in the future,&quot; said Rashid Abdi, who is the Horn of Africa project manager at the International Crisis Group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and Western countries appreciate its stability.
America&#39;s military and intelligence services work closely with the Ethiopians in the fight against terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and hardly any African country receives so much help from the West.
Ethiopia&#39;s economy has grown at an impressive pace.
Its infrastructure has improved tremendously, and the capital, Addis Ababa, even has a new commuter train.
The city&#39;s streets are typically quiet, safe and clean.
Although Ethiopia has not been a model of democracy. Human rights organizations have consistently spoken out about government repression, the country&#39;s opposition has been limited, and dissent has been effectively silenced.
Many have been expelled from the country, imprisoned, killed or driven far into the desert.
But this may be changing.
&quot;If you suppress people and they have no choice but to express themselves, this is what will happen,&quot; said Seyoum Teshome, a university teacher from central Ethiopia.
The entire youth is demonstrating.
One generation is protesting.
The complaints are diverse and cover everything from land use to the ruling coalition&#39;s stranglehold on power.
After last year&#39;s much-criticized elections, the ruling party and its allies won the last seat held by the opposition, and now holds all seats in parliament.
At the same time, tensions on the border with Eritrea are growing. Fighting along this tense and contested border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, which have been more or less defeated in recent years, may try to take advantage of the turmoil and re-arm.
Numerous factors explain why, after years of bubbling under the surface, bitter feelings are now about to explode.
The first seems seemingly innocuous: smartphones.
Only in the last few years have a large number of Ethiopians been able to communicate through social media, as cheaper smartphones have become more common and internet service has improved.
Even if the government shuts down access to Facebook and Twitter, as it often does, especially during protests, many people can still communicate through location-hiding network proxies.
Many young Ethiopians said this is how they came together for the protests.
Second, Ethiopia&#39;s two largest ethnic groups, the Oromo and the Amhara, get along better.
Oromos and Amharas are not natural allies.
For a very long time, the Amharas, who come from the predominantly Christian highlands of Ethiopia, prospered in politics and business by taking advantage of the Oromo, many of whom are Muslim, who live in the lowlands.
But this too is changing.
&quot;We are on the way to organizing under one umbrella,&quot; Oromo leader Mulatu Gemechu said.
The largest demonstrations have been in the Amhara and Oromo regions.
Many Amharas and Oromos feel that Ethiopia is unfairly ruled by the Tigre people. The nation covers about six percent of the population and controls the armed forces, intelligence, trade and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, was Ethiopia&#39;s prime minister for 17 years until he died of a mysterious illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could see around corners.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at spotting early signs of discontent and using secret emissaries to neutralize opponents.
&quot;The current administration doesn&#39;t have that kind of basic instinct,&quot; conflict analyst Abdi said.
Ethiopia&#39;s new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, was picked as a relative unknown to fill Meles&#39; boots.
Unlike Meles, who was from the tigre region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is from the south.
Analysts say he is not trusted by the security services controlled by the Tigers.
Many fear that this could lead to increased bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia was in such turmoil was in 2005, when thousands demonstrated against an election that analysts say appeared to have been rigged and then rigged by the government.
The ensuing crackdown left many protesters dead, though fewer than in recent months, and that period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts have praised Ethiopia&#39;s leaders for visionary infrastructure planning, such as a new commuter train, and significant strides in the fight against poverty.
But clearly, this has not stopped the internal intensification of contempt for the Ethiopian government.
And now it&#39;s starting to take on a dangerous, ethnic shape.
Last month, protesters in the Amhara city of Gondar attacked tiger-owned businesses, and anti-tigre hate is becoming increasingly common on social media.
Analysts say the protests put the United States and other Western allies in an awkward position.
The American government has been using Ethiopia as a base for air flights to neighboring Somalia, although it said some time ago that it had closed this base.
Although Western countries clearly want to support democracy, they also do not want their ally in an already unstable region to collapse.
“This,” Abdi said, “is a real balancing act.”
