Her husband, Andrew Coe, added: &quot;It was also a message to Americans about how to eat.&quot;
The couple, who live in Brooklyn Heights, are food historians.
Coe&#39;s latest book, Chop Suey, was about Chinese food in America, and Ziegelman told life in a Lower East Side tenement through food in his book 97 Orchard.
Their latest collaboration, A Square Meal, which Harper publishes on Tuesday, is a history of American food during the Great Depression of the 1930s.
Showing some sort of culinary solidarity of their own, they meet the editor for dinner at Eisenberg&#39;s Sandwich Shop, a tiny, unsophisticated lunch bar in the Flatiron District that has been in business since the 1929 stock market crash.
Ziegelman, 54, ordered a cream cheese and olive sandwich, and Coe, 57, had turkey, mashed potatoes and veggies.
