&quot;The shortbread was very popular,&quot; Ziegelman said.
There were peanut pretzels, liver pretzels, bean pretzels.
They were made from a preparation material and some cheap ingredient that was used to continue the actual preparation material.
Imagine eating enough peanuts to make up your dinner.
Coe grimaced.
&quot;It must have felt heavy in the stomach,&quot; he said.
In the years before the Depression, American tables, especially in rural areas, were like an eat-as-much-as-you-can buffet.
Groups of women cooked for the male farm workers, and fresh pie was served for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
Americans sent food to starving Europeans during World War I. A Square Meal chronicles the ways in which a nation coped with the fact that it was suddenly no longer a land of plenty.
&quot;At that time, food became a central, vexing subject for Americans,&quot; Coe said, explaining why he and his wife wanted to write about it.
Equally unnerving was the new, affordable diet: Mystery dishes like pretzels and boxes became staples, and box was “a great way to use leftovers,” Ziegelman noted, because chefs could hide less appealing ingredients under a layer of creamy sauce.
Fresh fruits were replaced by cheaper dried fruits.
Meat, which had been at the center of American meals for years, became a sparingly portioned luxury product.
Special combinations were tried, with calorie count and nutrient content being more important than taste or even common sense in the kitchen.
While doing research for the book, which also includes recipes, Ziegelman prepared a period dish in which fried onions were stuffed with peanut butter.
“It wasn&#39;t a popular addition to the dinner table,” Coe said.
Ziegelman elaborated: “It was unreal.”
Peanut butter is no match for fried onions.
This was characteristic of many household recipes.
Home economics experts such as Louise Stanley, director of the federal Home Office from 1923 to 1943, guided the nation&#39;s eating habits more than ever before or since.
By publishing recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines, they encouraged women to become &quot;budgeters&quot; and take on the challenge of turning lumps like mashed spaghetti and carrots into tasty portions.
A Square Meal is a celebration of historical delicacies.
Particularly tasty are the accounts of government responses to hungry citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover&#39;s let-me-eat-cake attitude.
While he publicly extolled the simple, country Iowa food of his childhood, he dined like the sophisticated millionaire he had become.
“He liked continental food, like fish and pickles,” Coe said.
He ate in an almost gilded dining room wearing a tuxedo.
He was awesomely out of everything.
President Roosevelt might have made the same mistake if his wife, Eleanor, had not encouraged him to lead by example with his own stomach.
As the book recounts, when Mrs. Roosevelt hired a housekeeper with no interest in taste, the White House became a place that &quot;served not only some of the worst food in Washington, but also some of the most wretchedly prepared food.&quot;
Many of the Depression-era eating habits were abandoned as soon as the country got back on its feet.
The legacy is our continued focus on calories and nutrition, Ziegelman said, and the way science is applied to cooking.
The couple said that while writing the book, they gained a better understanding of Ziegelman&#39;s mother&#39;s eating habits, such as how she couldn&#39;t throw away food.
“He was really afraid of wasting food,” Coe said.
Ziegelman recalled, “He even made people sick.”
There was a wind hat incident.
After the plates were cleared at Eisenberg&#39;s, he and Coe pulled out a dessert they had made at home: the plum dessert that President Roosevelt had for lunch.
“It&#39;s called plum mousse,” Ziegelman said, adding that a common ploy was to give humble recipes a flashy name.
There was no whipped cream in the dessert, just plums, some flour, sugar, water and cinnamon.
Everyone reluctantly dipped their spoons into the gooey, brown paste.
Surprisingly, it wasn&#39;t bad.
Coe faltered once and again.
Sounding like a positive budgeter, he told his wife: &quot;some chopped walnuts could help&quot;.
