Community legal centers turn away 160,000 people every year
More than 160,000 of the nation&#39;s most vulnerable are turned away from community legal centers every year as the sector prepares for the impact of further funding cuts on its already stretched-out operations.
In Queensland, three out of five people - mainly the elderly, migrants, vulnerable workers, victims of violence, those without the means to fight unfair evictions and the like - are already turned away when they seek free legal advice and representation.
The community&#39;s already stretched legal services are preparing for further cuts.
In June of next year, these legal centers are set to lose 30 percent of their federal funding.
Community Legal Centers Queensland director James Farrell said thousands of people were already being turned away each year, according to the latest National Association of Community Legal Centers census report.
Farrell said if the federal government&#39;s decision is not reversed, the situation will only get worse.
&quot;Queensland&#39;s community justice centers are chronically underfunded, meaning thousands of people are turned away from the essential services they need every year,&quot; he said.
People leaving abusive relationships with unmanageable and crippling debt, families in divorce, unfairly dismissed workers - all these people have legal problems, and this report shows that they are not getting the help they need.
The Federal Government will cut funding by 30% in June 2017, meaning thousands of vulnerable Queenslanders will be forced to navigate complex legal issues without help.
We appeal to the Attorney General and Queensland Senator George Brandis to immediately reverse these funding cuts so people can get the help they need with their legal problems.
Last year the state government delivered on its promise to raise legal aid funding to the national average.
Now is the time to look at the needs of community legal centers and their client communities, and the Palaszczuk Government should invest in this important work.
Donald Trump&#39;s campaign was sued after an employee was allegedly threatened with a gun
New York: Donald Trump&#39;s campaign has been sued for allegedly doing nothing after being told the campaign&#39;s North Carolina operations chief threatened a staffer with a gun in February while they were riding in a Jeep.
The incident was described in a lawsuit filed Wednesday in state court in Charlotte by former state campaign software intern Vincent Bordini.
Bordini said he waited for months for the situation to be handled internally before realizing &quot;it wasn&#39;t going to happen.&quot;
Chief Earl Phillip &quot;took out a pistol, put his right index finger on the trigger and pushed the barrel against Vincent&#39;s kneecap,&quot; Bordini said in the lawsuit.
After complaining to local and regional campaign managers, Bordini learned that at least four other people had had similar experiences with Phillip, the suit said.
&quot;Guns do not need to be fired to cause harm,&quot; Bordini said in the lawsuit.
The challenge comes just two days after the Republican presidential nominee caused outrage by telling a crowd in North Carolina that &quot;Second Amendment people&quot; -- generally understood to mean gun owners and gun owners -- could take action if his rival Hillary Clinton is elected and allowed to pick judges.
Trump&#39;s campaign said the media had taken his words out of context and that he does not support violence.
Bordin&#39;s lawsuit seeks compensation from the campaign for negligent supervision, and from Phillip for violence, assault and causing emotional shock.
Trump&#39;s spokeswoman Hope Hicks did not immediately respond to a request for comment.
Attempts to reach Phillip were unsuccessful.
WCCB, a local news affiliate in Charlotte, reported that Phillip recently left the campaign.
A call to his consulting firm Innovative Consulting Services was not immediately returned.
Republican presidential candidate Donald Trump&#39;s campaign has been controversial.
The case is Bordini v. Donald J. Trump for President Inc., 16-CS-14300, General Court of Justice, Superior Court Division Country of Mecklenburg (Charlotte).
Britain needs to channel the Olympic spirit and expand Heathrow
Heathrow brings regeneration and prosperity to the whole stomach, not just to local communities and across London.
