Adblock Plus and Facebook in a cat and mouse game about blocking ads
For companies that make money from online advertising, trying to bypass ad-blocking software is &quot;a game of cat and mouse,&quot; said one of the companies that make such software.
On Thursday, just two days after Facebook announced it would block ad blockers on its desktop pages, Adblock Plus released a blog post saying users can update the program&#39;s filters to once again block ads on the social network&#39;s pages.
On Tuesday, Facebook said it is changing the code around the ads on its websites to make it harder for ad blockers to detect which parts of the page are ads.
But now Adblock says it has circumvented the new code.
In a blog post, Adblock&#39;s Ben Williams wrote that &quot;this kind of back-and-forth between the open source ad-blocking community and its circumventors has been going on since ad-blocking was invented,&quot; and that it&#39;s possible Facebook will come up with its own solution soon.
The fact that the world&#39;s largest social media company has joined the fray is a strong indication of just how much of a pain ad blockers have become for the industry.
Around 200 million worldwide use ad blockers, according to last year&#39;s Pagefair and Adobe research. This is almost four times the number who used these programs in 2013.
1.03 million active daily users use Facebook on mobile devices, and mobile advertising now accounts for 84 percent of Facebook&#39;s ad revenue.
However, the company is pursuing ad blockers on desktop pages, as mobile ad blockers don&#39;t work on Facebook&#39;s mobile apps for the social network or Instagram, the representative said.
Desktop ads still bring in enough revenue for Facebook to consider such a move worth the investment.
Also on Tuesday, Facebook said it would update its “ad preferences” tool to give people more power over how ads are targeted to them.
On Thursday, Facebook argued that Adblock&#39;s new filters were troubling because they would also block some non-advertising content on the site.
&quot;This is not a good experience for people, and we have plans to address the issue,&quot; a Facebook representative said in an emailed statement.
Ad blockers are boring tools, which is why we&#39;ve focused instead on building tools like Ad Preferences that put people in control.
A woman was hit by a car on a Swiss highway, apparently due to suicide
The victim was lying on the highway in the middle of the night.
Police are appealing for witnesses after a woman was run over by multiple vehicles on a freeway in the early hours of Thursday in what appeared to be a suicide.
The incident happened on the A1 near Morges in the canton of Vaud just after midnight on Thursday.
The woman committed a &quot;desperate act&quot; and laid down on the road in the dark, where she was hit by several vehicles, Vaud police said in a statement.
The victim, who clearly tried to kill herself, was a 49-year-old Swiss woman who was hit by several vehicles, including a truck.
He died at the scene.
Several drivers related to the incident have already been questioned, but not all of them have been identified yet, said the police, who appeal to them and all eyewitnesses who witnessed the incident to come forward.
A criminal investigation has been initiated, which is a &quot;logical&quot; step in a situation like this, lawyer Gilles Hofstetter told Le Tribune de Geneve.
&quot;However, it remains to be seen whether any of the drivers involved will be charged.
Was it possible to avoid the collision?
It is up to the prosecutor to decide,&quot; Hofstetter said.
Two similar incidents in the last five years suggest that drivers are not being held accountable.
In both cases - both involving a person walking in the dark on a freeway - it was judged that motorists cannot expect to encounter a pedestrian on the freeway in the middle of the night, the paper said.
Last year, a police officer was cleared of manslaughter charges after he hit and killed a man who was lying on the A! Road near Paynerne one night in August 2014.
