The court found that the police, who were responding to the emergency call, drove in a justified manner, and that the presence of the man on the road was &quot;a completely exceptional and unpredictable situation&quot;, the judge said.
Anyone with information about Thursday&#39;s incident near Morges should call the police on 021 644 83 46 or 021 644 44 44.
NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
According to NASA&#39;s new climate model, Venus was probably once habitable.
Scientists at NASA&#39;s Goddard Institute for Space Studies developed a model to study Venus&#39; past using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to find out if Venus, with its hot, waterless surfaces and atmosphere filled with carbon dioxide, could have ever had Earth-like conditions.
Scientists have previously proposed that Venus&#39;s slow rotation rate is explained by its thick atmosphere.
But the latest simulation suggests that Venus could have had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere and still spin slowly.
The model also looked at the surface formation of early Venus.
The planet likely had areas drier than Earth, but there was once enough water and geographic variation to support life and protect against rapid water evaporation.
Early Venus also had the advantage of a 30 percent dimmer sun.
&quot;In the GISS model simulation, the slow rotation of Venus exposes its daytime side to the sun for almost two months at a time,&quot; GISS researcher Anthony Del Genio explained in a news release.
This warms the surface and produces rain, which creates a thick cloud layer that acts like an umbrella, shielding the surface from much of the sun&#39;s heat.
As a result, average climate temperatures are actually a few degrees cooler than Earth&#39;s current temperatures.
The model produced a story about the stages of Venus&#39; development that is similar to what planetary scientists had previously assumed.
Although Venus was likely once habitable, it was exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet light over several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapor burned in ultraviolet light.
When its hydrogen escaped, all that was left was a thick carbon dioxide atmosphere with its deadly greenhouse gas effects - the Venus we know today.
The researchers shared the results of their new Venus climate model in Geophysical Research Letters.
Patrick Roy is stepping down as Avalanche coach
Patrick Roy resigned as Colorado Avalanche coach and vice president of hockey affairs on Thursday, citing a lack of influence in the team&#39;s decision-making process.
Colorado vice president/general manager Joe Sakic confirmed the news and mentioned that the team will begin the search for a new coach immediately.
&quot;For the past three years, I have performed my duties as the Colorado Avalanche&#39;s vice president of hockey affairs and head coach with enthusiasm, passion and determination,&quot; Roy, 50, said in a statement.
I&#39;ve thought long and hard over the summer about how I can improve this team to give it the depth it needs and take it to a higher level.
In order to achieve this, the vision of the coach and VP of Hockey must be fully aligned with the vision of the organization.
He must also have the opportunity to influence decisions that affect the team&#39;s performance.
These conditions are currently not fulfilled.
Sakic, who hired Roy on May 23, 2013, thanked Roy for his contributions to the team.
&quot;Patrick told me today about his decision,&quot; Sakic said.
We appreciate all that he has done for the organization and wish him the best of luck in the future.
Roy was named the league&#39;s Jack Adams Award for Coach of the Year in his first season with the Avalanche in 2013-14.
He led the team to 112 points and a Central Division title, but Minnesota knocked off Colorado in the first round of the playoffs and the team has not made the playoffs in the past two years.
The Avalanche&#39;s 2015-16 season finished with 39 wins, 39 losses, and 4 ties, and the team lost by five points to the Wild to lose the Western Conference wild card playoff spot.
Hall of Fame goaltender Roy won four Stanley Cups - two with both the Montreal Canadiens and the Avalanche.
North Sea oil workers continue negotiations and postpone the strike
North Sea oil workers&#39; industrial action over pay will be postponed as all sides in the dispute sit down for a new round of talks, top negotiators said.
Strikes against oilfield services company Wood Group have been organized sporadically on North Sea rigs led by Royal Dutch Shell.
&quot;The Wood Group and the Unite and RMT unions can confirm that we have agreed to restart the process aimed at resolving the current dispute,&quot; the joint statement read.
We will be holding several all-day meetings over the next few weeks, starting early next week, to bring a fresh perspective to the issues.
Unions say their recent industrial action, which they say is the first in more than 25 years, was in protest against potential pay cuts of up to 30 percent.
This year, Wood Group cut North Sea contractors&#39; fees by around 9 percent due to negative market pressure.
The company&#39;s fee reduction follows the 10 percent reduction of contractors in its countries from 2014.
The company said the additional cuts would give the company the necessary wiggle room to weather the market downturn.
Shell, on the other hand, has cut thousands of people from its payroll and announced plans to exit oil and gas operations in up to 10 countries as the company streamlines operations following its giant merger with British energy company BG Group.
Energy companies are under pressure due to lower crude oil prices, and this economic situation is exacerbated by Britain&#39;s decision to leave the European Union in June.
Scottish MP Dave Anderson met union leaders earlier this week to discuss one of the biggest North Sea labor disputes in a generation.
He said the North Sea is essential to the region&#39;s economy.
&quot;We need an economy that works for the many, not just the few, both in the North Sea and in the whole country,&quot; he said in a statement.
In 2016, less than USD 1.4 billion of investments in new projects are expected in the North Sea, while the average of the previous five years has been around USD 7 billion.
Kepler measures the rotation speed of the stars in the Pleiades constellation
The latest mission of the Kepler space telescope has helped astronomers gather the most complete list of the rotation rates of stars in the Pleiades constellation.
The new data will help astronomers understand why the cluster&#39;s stars rotate at varying speeds, as well as how rotation periods relate to planet formation.
&quot;We hope that by comparing our results to other star clusters, we will now learn more about the relationship between a star&#39;s mass, its age, and even its solar system history,&quot; Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech&#39;s Pasadena Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis, said in a press release
The Pleiades star cluster is located 445 light years from Earth.
Many of the cluster&#39;s stars were born about 125 million years ago, and are just now reaching adulthood.
They are now running at their peak.
At their peak rotation speed, these maturing stars eject large amounts of stellar wind.
As these winds pass through the stars&#39; magnetic fields, they put the brakes on the stars.
As a star ages, its rotation rate begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by watching for the appearance of recognizable starspots, such as sunspots.
The most recent list of stellar rotation rates suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares stars to dancers, the bigger ones doing pirouettes slower than the smaller ones.
&quot;In the &#39;ballet&#39; of the Pleiades, we see that slow rotators tend to be more massive, while the fastest rotators tend to be very light stars,&quot; Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades star cluster is so close, it is an ideal cosmic laboratory for evaluating the properties of stars by their rotation rates.
&quot;The Pleiades star cluster provides an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation that include both directions, younger and older,&quot; Rebull said.
We still have a lot to learn about how, when and why stars slow down their rotation rate and hang up their &#39;dancing shoes&#39;, so to speak.
Rebull and his colleagues described their latest analysis of the rotation rates of the Pleiades in three papers to be published soon in the Astronomical Journal.
